  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Your sleep tracker told you last night that you got 47 minutes of deep sleep. That number is, in all likelihood, made up. Not fraudulently — nobody sat in a lab inventing it — but made up in the way that any confident answer to an unanswerable question is made up. The device on your wrist cannot measure your brain. It measures your wrist. Everything it tells you about sleep architecture — the tidy breakdown into light, deep, and REM — is an inference, run through a proprietary algorithm, benchmarked against population averages, and delivered to you at 6 a.m. as though it were a fact about your body. It is not a fact about your body. The problem is that you are now making decisions based on it.</p>
</section>

<section id="what-it-measures" class="reveal">
  <h2>What It Actually Measures</h2>
  <p>The clinical gold standard for sleep staging is polysomnography — PSG — conducted in a sleep lab with electrodes on your scalp recording electroencephalogram (EEG) data. Brain waves change in characteristic ways across sleep stages: slow delta waves dominate deep sleep, theta and alpha patterns mark lighter stages, and REM produces a signature fast, low-amplitude signal that resembles wakefulness. These are not subtle differences. They are the measurement. Everything else is a proxy.</p>
  <p>Consumer wearables use two primary sensors: an accelerometer, which detects movement, and photoplethysmography (PPG), which measures heart rate, heart rate variability, and sometimes respiration and skin temperature by shining light through your skin. Proprietary algorithms then correlate these signals against patterns seen in PSG studies — slower, more regular heart rate suggests deep sleep; stillness with elevated heart rate suggests REM — and produce a sleep stage classification. This is not a worse version of EEG. It is a categorically different measurement, inferring neural states from peripheral physiology. The gap is not engineering. It is physics.</p>
  <p>HRV-sleep correlations do exist at the population level. They are also highly variable between individuals. The algorithm trained on a sample population may perform well in aggregate and poorly on you specifically — and you will never know which, because you don't have a control condition.</p>
</section>

<section id="what-it-claims" class="reveal">
  <h2>What It Claims to Tell You</h2>
  <p>A 2023 meta-analysis examining consumer sleep trackers against PSG found that no wearable device achieved clinical-grade accuracy in sleep stage classification, though industry defenders like Oura and Fitbit argue their algorithms improve with user data over time and cite internal studies showing 80-90% accuracy in controlled settings. Across devices tested — including widely used commercial trackers — the recurring failure mode was misclassifying wakefulness as light sleep, producing inflated estimates of both total sleep time and sleep quality. The trackers performed reasonably well at the coarsest binary distinction — sleep versus wake — and reasonably well on total sleep duration. Sleep stage breakdowns, the feature most prominently marketed, were the least reliable outputs.</p>
  <p>Companies like Fitbit and Apple can publish whatever staging algorithm they want with no independent clinical validation requirement, profiting from billions in annual sales while studies critical of their accuracy often come from independent academics without industry funding. This is one sentence in the story, not its headline — the deeper problem is structural, not conspiratorial. But it does mean that when a company cites "accuracy" in its marketing, it is almost certainly citing its own internal study, conducted on its own hardware, under conditions it selected.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal">
  <p>"The tracker performs reasonably well at distinguishing sleep from wakefulness. The stage breakdown — the feature most prominently marketed — is the least reliable output."</p>
</aside>

<section id="what-that-does-to-you" class="reveal">
  <h2>What That Does to You</h2>
  <p>In 2017, Kelly Baron and colleagues published a case series in the <em>Journal of Clinical Sleep Medicine</em> describing patients who presented with insomnia complaints that were directly caused or amplified by sleep tracker data. They named the phenomenon orthosomnia: a preoccupation with achieving perfect measured sleep that itself disrupts sleep. The patients weren't imagining bad sleep — they were experiencing it. The tracker was producing it.</p>
  <p>The feedback loop runs like this. The device reports low deep sleep. The user wakes anxious about their sleep quality. That anxiety elevates arousal — cortisol, rumination, hypervigilance — which is precisely the physiological state incompatible with falling and staying asleep. The next night's sleep is worse. The score drops further. The anxiety tightens. The Baron paper was a case series, not a controlled trial, but its findings align with established mechanisms of sleep anxiety, making orthosomnia a credible risk backed by clinical patterns rather than just a tentative signal. But the mechanism is not speculative. Sleep onset anxiety is well-documented; the question orthosomnia raises is only whether a device can reliably deliver it at scale. Millions of people checking their sleep scores every morning suggests the answer is yes.</p>
  <p>The irony is structural. The device is sold as a tool for optimizing rest. The optimization process — monitoring, scoring, reacting — is a reliable delivery mechanism for the cognitive arousal patterns that prevent rest. You cannot hack your way to sleep. Sleep is, at its neurological core, a relinquishment of control. The tracker monetizes the opposite impulse.</p>
</section>

<section id="what-to-do-with-it" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the Tracker Is Actually Good For</h2>
  <p>None of this means the device is useless. Total sleep time estimates are reasonably accurate — if the tracker says you slept six hours, you probably slept close to six hours. Sleep versus wake detection is decent. And longitudinal trend data — not the nightly score, but the direction of weeks of data — can surface patterns worth noticing: consistent short sleep on work nights, or disrupted sleep during periods of elevated stress. That is genuinely useful information, provided you are not interrogating each data point.</p>
  <p>The clinical implication is precise: use the tracker the way you would use a bathroom scale for fitness. A weekly average tells you something. Checking it three times a day while adjusting your posture tells you nothing except how anxious you are. The sleep score is not a grade. It is a low-resolution signal built from imprecise sensors, processed by an unvalidated algorithm, and calibrated to population averages that may not describe you.</p>
  <p>If your tracker is making you anxious about your sleep, that anxiety is now a more reliable predictor of poor sleep than whatever score the device produced. The most evidence-based thing you can do with a bad sleep score is ignore it. That is not a defeat. That is the finding.</p>
</section>

